[4] India (Kerala)
Date: Sun 6 Jun 2010
Source: Deccan Harald
<http://www.deccanherald.com/content/73815/dengue-fever-spreading-kasargod-taluk.html>


In 2010, a total of 45 people have suffered from dengue in the district and
out of it; 30 belonged to Kasargod taluk [a taluk is a division of local
government within a district in some Indian states]. Maximum number of
cases are reported in Kuttikol Gram Panchayat, where 15 people were
reported to be suffering from dengue fever and one died.

In 2009, 48 people had dengue fever, wherein 30 people belonged to Kasargod
taluk. Fever, eye strain, body pain, muscle pain, vomiting, stomach pain,
redness in stool, and weakness are the symptoms of dengue fever. The fever
[virus] spreads through mosquitos belonging to _Aedes_ family [genus].
Mosquitos in areca nut [the Areca palm (_Areca catechu_)] rubber
plantations, too, may cause [transmit] the disease [virus].

--
communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[An 11 Jun 2010 report in the Times of India
(<http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/India/Kerala-in-grip-of-viral-outbreak-25-dead/articleshow/6035088.cms>)
indicated that there was an outbreak of fever in Kerala, including dengue
cases, with 12 new cases on 10 Jun 2010.

A map showing the location of Kerala state on the southwest tip of India
