[7] Guadeloupe
Date: Tue 8 Jun 2010
Source: Maxi Mini.com [in French, trans. Corr. SB, edited]
<http://www.maximini.fr/fr/guadeloupe/actualite/info-antilles/info_antilles.asp?num=22389>


The recent increase in the number of people who consulted their physician
for dengue is unlikely to reassure the health services. Headache, high
fever: for 6 months, the infectious disease [virus] transmitted by _Aedes
aegypti_ has indeed resulted in the hospitalization of more than 7300
people in Guadeloupe.

The sectors most affected involve the Grande Terre, particularly Le Moule,
Saint-Francois and Les Abymes, and more recently Three Rivers and
Terre-de-Haut to Basse-Terre. Given the high temperatures and increased
rainfall, an increase of mosquitoes and an increase of virus circulation
are still feared.

The epidemic occurred since December [2009] comes at an unusual period, but
still small-scale compared to that of the traditional rainy season,
according to Jean-Louis Chappert, a medical epidemiologist in the National
Institute of Veille Sanitaire (INVS ) in the Region.

The measures adopted by the Management Committee of dengue epidemics who
last met on 7 May [2010] remains valid: the maintenance of epidemiological
surveillance, implementation of a communication plan (posters, radio spots,
mobilizing partners and networks), broadening and strengthening of control
operations on sensitive sites (schools, early childhood) and enlargement of
spraying insecticides.

The gradual increase in the number of cases clinically and biologically
confirmed by sentinel physicians [physicians who receive dengue cases, not
physicians who themselves become ill. - Mod.TY], forcast a rainy season
particularly conducive to the spread of dengue.

What extra care with emphasis on electric diffusers insecticides (inside)
and mosquito coils (outside) and removing items that may accumulate
rainwater around dwellings (flower pots, clay pots, vases .. etc.).

In case of high fever, avoid taking aspirin and anti-inflammatories and
consult your doctor.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This report indicates that the dengue outbreak on Guadeloupe Island continues.

An interactive map showing the location of Guadeloupe in the Caribbean can
