[8] Martinique
Date: Fri 11 Jun 2010
Source: DOMactu.com [in French, trans. Corr. SB, edited]
<http://www.domactu.com/actualite/106102116760937/martinique-dengue-premier-cas-mortel/>


Dengue: 1st fatal case in La Martinique
---------------------------------------
A girl of 10 years died on Monday [7 Jun 2010] after contracting dengue
virus. The child, suffering from sickle cell anemia could not resist the
virus. Currently, analyses are still being conducted in Guyana, to confirm
that the dengue virus was the leading cause of death.

To date, nearly 500 people have contracted the virus, some developing
severe forms such as DHF. As just illustrated by this terrible tragedy, it
is unfortunately the children who are the most vulnerable.

There is at present no vaccine or effective treatment. Only preventive
actions can prevent the spread of the mosquito vector of the virus, _Aedes
aegypti_. This [mosquito] can breed in containers such as clay vessels,
metal drums, tanks cement used for preservation of domestic water, and
abandoned plastic containers, old tires and other objects of accumulated
rainwater. It is also highly recommended to sleep under a mosquito net, use
repellents and cover up skin, to avoid bites.

[byline: Mary Jean]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A subsequent report of Sun 13 Jun 2010 in DOMactu.com
(<http://www.domactu.com/actualite/106122041973437/martinique-epidemie-de-dengue-deja-2-morts/>)
reported an additional death due to dengue virus infection. Another report
that appeared on 13 Jun 2010 in Zinfos974.com
(<http://www.zinfos974.com/Dengue-aux-Antilles-trois-deces-suspects_a18538.html?com>)
indicated that on Martinique 118 patients have been hospitalized with 57
classical dengue cases, 21 severe cases and 4 cases of DHF. There are 15
other cases under study.

A map showing the location of Martinique in the Caribbean can be accessed
at
<http://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/namerica/caribb/martnque.htm>.
